@Node "intro" "Introduction"

@{u}Introduction@{uu}


With @{i}Sample Dumper@{ui}, you are able to dump soundsamples either via MIDI or
SCSI to your synthesizer.




@Endnode
@Node "requirements" "Requirements"

@{u}Requirements@{uu}


@{i}Sample Dumper@{ui} requires at least:

  - MUI 3.8

  - SCSI bus (if you want to use SCSI Dump)

  - a MIDI interface hooked up to your serial port (if you want to use
    MIDI sample dump)

  - Some musical device which is able to hold samples, i.e. a synthesizer
    or a sampler. See also @{" Tested equipment " link "tested"}.
    If you want to use SCSI dump, your synth must have an SCSI bus, of course.


@Endnode
@Node "features" "Features"

@{u}Features@{uu}


  - SDS (MIDI Sample Dump Standard), with open and closed MIDI loop

  - SMDI (SCSI Musical Data Interchange Protocol)

  - Utilizes your serial boards, like the IO-Extender or Multiface III

  - Sample Dumper is Freeware!

  - Supports various @{" sample formats " link "sampleformats"}

  - Locale support

  - ARexx port


Note that in this version the @{" Request Dump " link "gadgets"} action is not yet
implemented. The reason for this is, I wanted to get this program released,
and I still have problems with SCSI dump request.


@Endnode
@Node "sampleformats" "Sample formats"

@{u}Known Sample formats@{uu}


@{i}Sample Dumper@{ui} knows the following sample formats, either if loaded
from disk or saved to disk.


  - AIFF 8/16-bit mono/stereo

  - WAVE 8/16-bit mono/stereo

  - IFF-8SVX mono


@Endnode
@Node "gadgets" "Gadgets and Menus"

@{u}Menus@{uu}


  @{i}Project@{ui}

    About...            Show information about this program.

    About MUI...        Show the MUI about requester.

    Quit                Quit the program.

  @{i}Settings@{ui}

    Dump Method         Here you can choose between two dump procedure
                        methods:

                        MIDI (SDS)    MIDI Sample Dump Standard Protocol.
                                      A serial MIDI connection will be used
                                      to send or receive the sample.

                        SCSI (SMDI)   SCSI Musical Data Interchange Protocol.
                                      The sample is sent or received via the
                                      computer's and synth's SCSI hosts.

    SCSI Device/Unit    The device name of the Amiga's SCSI host. The synth's
                        SCSI host must be connected to your Amiga host.
                        Some people may call this a SCSI net. Make sure your
                        synth has a SCSI-ID which is unused on your Amiga.

    Serial Device/Unit  The serial device driver and a suitable unit. Known
                        devices are serial.device, gvpser.device,
                        duart.device, artser.device.

    SysEx Channel       The MIDI SDS protocol requires a system exclusive
                        channel on which it is exchanged. Please realize
                        that this is not one of the 16 MIDI music channels!
                        This value is ranging from 0 to 127. Your synth
                        should be setup with the same sysex ID.

    Open Midi Loop      When enabled, SampleDumper assumes the synth is hooked
                        up in an open Midi loop, ie the Amiga Midi-out is
                        connected to the Midi-in of the synth. This can be useful
                        in batch dumps to avoid checking for Midi handshaking.

    Save Settings       Save the current settings as tooltypes of the application
                        program.

    MUI...              Open the MUI settings window for this application.




@{u}Gadgets@{uu}


  @{i}Transmit Sample@{ui}

    (file name)         Choose the sample file which is to be transfered
                        into your synthesizer.
                        If you have chosen a file, it will be tested to
                        see if it's got a valid @{" sample format " link "sampleformats"}.

    Frequency           This is the sample rate of your chosen file, in Hz.
                        (will be filled if you select a file)

    Length              This is the sample data length of your chosen file,
                        given in @{" sample words " link "sampleword"}.
                        (will be filled if you select a file)

    Loop Start          This is the loop start point of your chosen file,
                        given in @{" sample words " link "sampleword"}.
                        (will be filled if you select a file)
                        Valid range is 0 - (length-1).

    Loop Stop           This is the loop stop point of your chosen file,
                        given in @{" sample words " link "sampleword"}.
                        (will be filled if you select a file)
                        Valid range is 0 - (length-1).

    Bits                You can see the digital resolution in bits here.
                        (will be filled if you select a file)

    Tracks              Here's the number of tracks.
                        1 = mono, 2 = stereo sample.
                        (will be filled if you select a file)

    Sample Number       Here's the sample number where your sample will
                        be accessible in your synthesizer. The valid
                        range depends on how your synthesizer stores its
                        objects.

                        Note: With MIDI Dump, you may enter zero here (0),
                        which means your synth will choose a sample number
                        on its own. With SCSI Dump, you MUST deliver a
                        valid number here.

    Send Dump           Hit this button to immediately start the dump
                        procedure. A progress window will pop up and give
                        you the chance to abort the procedure.


  @{i}Receive Sample@{ui}

    (file name)         Choose the sample filename which is to be received
                        (i.e. requested) from your synthesizer.

    Sample Number       Here you can enter the number of the desired sample
                        residing in your synth. If it does not hold a
                        sample at this number, the dump procedure will fail.

    Save as             Choose one of @{i}Sample Dumper@{ui}'s supported
                        @{" sample formats " link "sampleformats"}.

    Request Dump        Hit this button to immediately start the dump
                        receive/request procedure. A progress window will
                        pop up and give you the chance to abort the
                        procedure.

@Endnode
@Node "sampleword" "Sampleword"

@{u}Sample word@{uu}


A sample word consists of several bytes, depending on the sample resolution
and the number of channels.

Examples:

  An 8-bit mono sample has a sample word size of 1 byte.

  A 16-bit stereo sample has a sample word size of 4 bytes.

  A 12-bit mono sample has a sample word size of 2 bytes.

  A 16-bit 4-channel surround sample has a sample word size of 8 bytes.


@Endnode
@Node "mididump" "Send with MIDI/SDS"

@{u}How to dump a sample via MIDI/SDS into your synth@{uu}


@{i}Hardware setup@{ui}

 What you need for this protocol is a standard closed-MIDI-loop. That is,
 have Amiga-MIDI-out connected to synth-MIDI-in, and Amiga-MIDI-in connected
 to synth-MIDI-out. As proposed by the SDS protocol, @{i}Sample Dumper@{ui} will
 try to use handshaking but may fall down to not using handshaking if an
 open-MIDI-loop is detected (see below).



@{i}Software setup@{ui}

 Choose "MIDI" @{" Dump Method " link "gadgets"} and enter the serial driver's name
 to which you have hooked up your MIDI interface. Don't forget to adjust
 the unit number.

 If you have only one synth connected to your MIDI setup which is capable
 of MIDI Sample Dump, you should set the synth's MIDI channel parameter to
 zero. This means, it will respond to all Sample Dump sysex messages. In
 this case the @{" MIDI channel " link "gadgets"} number on the Amiga side doesn't
 matter.

 If you have more than one SDS-capable synths connected, you should set
 their sysex IDs to different values, e.g. 1 and 2. In @{i}Sample Dumper@{ui},
 choose with @{" MIDI channel " link "gadgets"} the sysex ID of the synth which is
 to receive the sample.

 Finally, you choose a sample within the @{" Transmit Sample " link "gadgets"} area, then
 press @{" Send Dump " link "gadgets"} to start the dump.

 The progress-window is usually showing the target's identifier name. It will
 be empty here because the SDS protocol does not feature a target
 identification (unlike the @{" SMDI protocol " link "scsidump"}).

 If @{i}Sample Dumper@{ui} doesn't get a response from your synth, you will be asked
 to continue without handshaking or cancel the operation. Choose "continue"
 if you have hooked up an open-MIDI-loop (that is, only the Amiga->synth
 direction is up). In this case, the sample is sent without any handshaking.
 Choose "cancel" if you think you have selected a wrong serial device :-)



 See also @{" Receive with MIDI/SDS " link "midireceive"}, @{" Send with SCSI/SMDI " link "scsidump"},
 or @{" Receive with SCSI/SMDI " link "scsireceive"}.

@Endnode
@Node "midireceive" "Receive with MIDI/SDS"

@{u}How to receive a sample via MIDI/SDS from your synth@{uu}


@{i}Hardware setup@{ui}

 Please connect the hardware exactly as described in the @{" Send with MIDI/SDS " link "mididump"}
 section.


@{i}Software setup@{ui}

 (not yet implemented)



 See also @{" Send with MIDI/SDS " link "midisend"}, @{" Send with SCSI/SMDI " link "scsidump"},
 or @{" Receive with SCSI/SMDI " link "scsireceive"}.

@Endnode
@Node "scsidump" "Send with SCSI/SMDI"

@{u}How to dump a sample via SCSI/SMDI into your synth@{uu}


@{i}Hardware setup@{ui}

 First, you must have your Amiga connected properly to your synth device.
 Both the Amiga and the synth must have a SCSI host, otherwise it is not
 possible to perform the SMDI protocol.
 You might look up your synth's manual to see if it has got a SCSI host
 which must have an external connector. Now, put a SCSI cable from your
 synth's external port to your Amiga's external SCSI port. You MUST ensure
 your synth and your Amiga have devices with different SCSI-IDs, otherwise
 there will be big difficulties.
 Once you have both systems up and running together, you may check the
 IDs with some SCSI tools, e.g. SCSIConfig or HDToolbox. These tools should
 show your synth at its SCSI-ID.
 You should see your Amiga SCSI devices from the synth.


@{i}Software setup@{ui}

 Select "SCSI" @{" Dump Method " link "gadgets"}, then enter your SCSI-driver's name
 in the according input field. Choose the unit matching your synth's ID.
 After that you should specify a valid @{" Sample Number " link "gadgets"}. The gadget
 for this resides in the @{" Transmit Sample " link "gadgets"} area.

 Choose a sample, either by typing its name or by using the file requester.
 You might also want to drop a sample with its icon into the main window.
 If your sample is identified correctly, the fields @{" Frequency " link "gadgets"},
 @{" Length " link "gadgets"}, @{" Loop Start " link "gadgets"} and @{" Loop Stop " link "gadgets"} should
 become initialized. You may alter them, but normally you don't want to.
 Now you hit the @{" Send Dump " link "gadgets"} button and off we go!

 It might happen that Sample Dumper cannot identify your synth as a
 SMDI-capable device. In this case you can select "continue" and the sample
 dump procedure will go on, ignoring the fault.



 See also @{" Receive with MIDI/SDS " link "midireceive"}, @{" Send with MIDI/SDS " link "mididump"},
 or @{" Receive with SCSI/SMDI " link "scsireceive"}.

@Endnode
@Node "scsireceive" "Receive with SCSI/SMDI"

@{u}How to receive a sample via SCSI/SMDI from your synth@{uu}


@{i}Hardware setup@{ui}

 Please connect the hardware exactly as described in the @{" Send with SCSI/SMDI " link "scsidump"}
 section.


@{i}Software setup@{ui}

 (not yet implemented)



 See also @{" Receive with MIDI/SDS " link "midireceive"}, @{" Send with MIDI/SDS " link "mididump"},
 or @{" Send with SCSI/SMDI " link "scsidump"}.

@Endnode
@Node "rexx" "ARexx port"

@{u}ARexx port@{uu}


The ARexx port name is "SAMPLEDUMPER". Here is a list of commands with
parameters:

Command    Template    Description
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
LOAD          FILE/A      Load and check a file.

DUMP          FILE        Dump the give file with the current method (SMDI or
                          SDS). If FILE is omitted, the currently loaded
                          file is dumped.

SAMPLENUMBER  NUMBER/N/A  Set a sample number for both dump directions.
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Ok this list is not large but it's enough to initiate a batch dump.

An ARexx-script named "Batchdump.rexx" is supplied which prompts the user to
select several samples to dump via SampleDumper. Then, enter the sample number
to start the dump with. This number is increased by 1 after each dumped
sample.


